T1  - Factor substitution, ex ante and ex post
AU  - Winston, Gordon C.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 1
IS  - 2
SP  - 145
EP  - 163
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(74)90004-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387874900042
AB  - The amount of labor used per unit of capital stock (or investment) can be varied by any one of four quite different mechanisms. Two of these – changes in crew size and in capital utilization – are variable even ex post. These mechanisms are systemmatically related and all induce factor substitution in the same (neoclassical) direction with a change in relative factor prices. The conditions necessary to support the view that ‘factor prices don't matter’ are shown to be terribly stringent.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The cost and composition of Indian exports
AU  - P. Staelin, Charles
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 1
IS  - 2
SP  - 129
EP  - 143
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(74)90003-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387874900030
AB  - India has a history of export promotion policies extending back into the 1950's. These policies seem to have been applied without regard to comparative advantage and this study indicates the high cost of India's disregard for economic efficiency. Using the domestic resource cost concept as the criterion for measuring relative export efficiency, the present structure of Indian exports is examined on both the sectoral and product level. The results show not only an unacceptably wide divergence in the domestic resource cost of exports on the margin - indicating a misallocation of resources in the export sector - but also an export incentive system which fails to select India's most efficient exports.
ER  - 
